: Many women lie about being raped because they feel guilty after having consensual sex\n\nTruth: Women rarely make false reports about sexual assault. Reporting rape is one of the most under reported crimes that happens in Canada.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMyth 2: Women who are sexually assaulted ask for it by the way they dress or act.\n\nTruth: There is no excuse for rape and no one asks for it. This my perpetuates the victim blaming and takes the responsibility away from the rapist and places it on the victim\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMyth 3: Women fantasize about being raped.\n\nTruth: No woman fantasizes about being raped. When people have sexual fantasies of aggressive sex or seduction, they choose the circumstances and characteristics of their seducer and the fantasy can be turned off if it becomes uncomfortable or threatening. With rape, the act is unwanted and the victim is unable to control the assault or stop it. In rape, the victim is never in control. There is a big difference between fantasy and reality.\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n<strong> </strong>Myth 4: Women who are drunk are willing to engage in any kind of sexual activity.\n\nTruth: The fact that a woman has been drinking does not imply consent. Alcohol and drugs can render someone mentally incapable to give consent; therefore engaging in sexual activity with someone who has been drinking could lead to a sexual assault.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMyth 5: Women say \"NO\" when they really mean, \"YES\".\n\nTruth: When a woman says \"NO\" she means, NO. This is another excuse to promote victim blaming and view men as controlled only by their sexual urges. This myth places blame on anything other that the person who is the rapist.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSource:\n\nDartmouthCollege (2013). Sexual Abuse Awareness. <i>Rape Myths</i>. Retrieved March 10, 2013 from <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><a href=\"http://www.dartmouth.edu/sexualabuse/educated/rape_myths.html\">http://www.dartmouth.edu/sexualabuse/educated/rape_myths.html</a